To print the escaped character `\\x9b`, which corresponds to the ASCII bell character (also known as `\a`), you can use the following code snippet in Python:

```python
print("\\x9b")
```

When executed, this will display the string containing the escape sequence `\x9b`. However, keep in mind that the actual output will depend on your environment—it might produce a sound alert (bell) or simply show the escape sequence itself without any audible effect.

In some environments where the system supports ANSI escape codes, running this command in a terminal window might cause the terminal to emit a beep sound. This behavior varies between operating systems and terminal emulators.

Here's an example of how you might see the result in a Unix-like shell:

```shell
$ python3
>>> print("\\x9b")
\x9b
```

Please note that the actual visual representation (`\x9b`) won't appear as a beep; instead, it will just be printed out as part of the console output. If you want to trigger the actual beep sound, you should run the script within a compatible terminal emulator configured to respond to such escape sequences.
